1.3

Derive an equation for doubling time in an exponentially growing population, and derive one for tripling time.

If \(N(t) = N(0)e^{rt}\), and we want to double or triple the initial population, we respectively seek the ratios \(\frac{N(t)}{N(0)} = 2\) and \(\frac{N(t)}{N(0)} = 3\). How long that takes means we must then solve for \(t\). If \(x = e^{rt}\), solving for \(t\) would require taking the log (natural) of both sides, then dividing both sides by \(r\), leaving us with \(\frac{\log (x)}{r} = t\). For doubling time let \(x = 2\) and for tripling time let \(x = 3\).

1.5

The human population on a small island nation is said to be doubling every 20 years. What would be the value of \(r\) (assuming an exponential model)? In \(2 = \frac{N(20)}{N(0)} = e^{r(20)}\), then we are trying to solve for \(r\). In this case, we take the natural log of both sides and divide by \(t = 20\), giving \(r = \frac{\log (2)}{20} = 0.03465736\).

This graphical relationship demonastrates why the section just read is called density-independent change.

1.12

Beginning with the exponential equation, assume that the rate of change decreases linearly with population density (i.e., substitute \(a - bN\) for \(r\)). Show what substitutions you need to make to write the equation in its more biologically sensible form (i.e., with the intrinsic rate of natural incrase and the carrying capacity evident). How do \(a\) and \(b\) of the linear approximation relate to the \(r\) and \(K\) of \(\frac{\mathrm{d}N}{\mathrm{d}t} = rN\left(\frac{K-N}{K}\right)\)?

The exponential eqaution is \(\frac{dN}{dt} = rN\), and replacing \(r\) with \(a - bN\) gives us \(\frac{dN}{dt} = N\left(a - bN\right)\). In this case, as the rate of change decreases linearly with population density, like 1.11, \(a\) would be the per-capita growth rate when density is near 0 and \(b\) would be the negative linear relationship between density and per-capita growth rate.

1.13

Assuming that a population grows according to the logistic equation, what is the value of the population density that will give the maximum growth rate?

The maximum population growth rate will occur when we examine the relationship between density and rate of change. We can calculte the rate of change by taking the derivative of the logistic equation with respect to \(N\), and solving for \(N\). Specifically: \[\frac{\mathrm{d} \frac{\mathrm{d}N}{\mathrm{d}t}}{\mathrm{d} N} = \left(\frac{\mathrm{d} \left(rN\left(\frac{K - N}{K}\right)\right)}{\mathrm{d} N}\right) = r - 2r\left(\frac{N}{K}\right) \] Setting the second derivative to 0 and solving for \(N\) will give us \(N^* = \frac{K}{2}\), meaning that the maximal rate of change will be at half of the carrying capacity.

1.15 (Skip)

In the Bleasdale and Nedler equation, the “yield” of the equation effectively represents the input into the next generation if, instread of total crop yield in terms of biomass, it is expressed as the number of offspring. Write an equation, using the basic Bleasdale and Nedler formulation, that relates the population density this year to that we expect next year, assuming 100% mortality *i.e., an annual species). If you pot the number this year on the \(x\) axis and the number next year on the \(y\) axis, what does the functional form look like for various valies of the parameter \(b\)?

The equation will be: \[N_{t+1} = \frac{N_t k}{\left(1 + \alpha N_t\right)^b}\] With various values of \(b\), \(N_{t+1}\) as a function of \(N_t\) woudld be:

# Set up parameters
b.vals <- seq(from = 0.75, to = 5, by = 0.1)
n.b.vals <- length(b.vals)
N.vals <- seq(from = 0, to = 4.5, by = 0.01)
n.N.vals <- length(N.vals)
N.mat_1.15 <- matrix(data = NA, nrow = n.b.vals, ncol = n.N.vals)
k <- 1
alpha <- 1

# Loop over each value of N
for (i in 1:n.b.vals) {
  N.mat_1.15[i, ] <- (N.vals*k) / (1 + alpha*N.vals)^b.vals[i]
}

# Make a function for colors then give give that function the number of b values
col.func <- colorRampPalette(c("red", "blue"))
cols4b <- col.func(n.b.vals)

# Make a blank plot then loop over the rows of the matrix with different b values
plot(x = NA, type = "n", xlab = "Nt", ylab = "Nt1", xlim = c(0, 4), ylim = c(0,0.9), las = 1)
for (j in 1:n.b.vals) {
    lines(x = N.vals, y = N.mat_1.15[j,], col = cols4b[j])
}

1.16

Using the logistic map and starting with 0.1 individuals, project the population 50 times with values of \(\lambda =\) 0.1, 1.5, 2.0, 3.0, and 3.5. How does the time series change as a function of \(\lambda\)?

N0_1.16 <- 0.01
lambda.vec <- c(1, 1.5, 2, 3, 3.5)
n.lambdas <- length(lambda.vec)
n.steps_1.16 <- 50
vec.steps_1.16 <- 1:n.steps_1.16
N.mat <- matrix(data = NA, nrow = n.lambdas, ncol = n.steps_1.16) # each row will be a 
N.mat[,1] <- N0_1.16 # it fills the entire column with initial N0

for (i in 1:n.lambdas) {
  for (j in 2:n.steps_1.16) {
    N.mat[i, j] <- lambda.vec[i]*N.mat[i, j-1]*(1 - N.mat[i, j-1])
  }
}

plot(NA, type = "n", xlim = c(0, n.steps_1.16), ylim = c(0, max(N.mat)), xlab = "Time step", ylab = "Density", las = 1)
  lines(x = vec.steps_1.16, y = N.mat[1,] , lwd = 1.5) # lwd is the "line width"
  lines(x = vec.steps_1.16, y = N.mat[2,] , lwd = 1.5, col = "red")
  lines(x = vec.steps_1.16, y = N.mat[3,] , lwd = 1.5, col = "blue")
  lines(x = vec.steps_1.16, y = N.mat[4,] , lwd = 1.5, col = "orange")
  lines(x = vec.steps_1.16, y = N.mat[5,] , lwd = 1.5, col = "purple")

The time series change by first increasing more rapidly with increasing \(\lambda\), as you can see in the first few time steps. For the larger values of \(\lambda\), the time series begin to fluctuate.

1.18

Plot \(N_{t+1}\) against \(N_t\) for the Beverton and Holt model, the Hassell model, and the Ricker model (eqns. 28–30), and compare them. Let \(\lambda = 1\), \(\alpha = 1\), and \(b = 2\). Once you get the three models on a spreadsheet, experiment with different values of \(b\), \(\lambda\), and \(\alpha\).

steps <- 21
N_BH <- vector(length = steps, mode = "numeric")
N_H <- vector(length = steps, mode = "numeric")
N_R <- vector(length = steps, mode = "numeric")
N_BH[1] <- 0.05
N_H[1] <- 0.05
N_R[1] <- 0.05
for (i in 2:steps) {
  N_BH[i] <- (1*N_BH[i-1]) / (1 + 1*N_BH[i-1])
  N_H[i] <- (1*N_H[i-1]) / ((1 + 1*N_H[i-1])^2)
  N_R[i] <- N_R[i-1]*exp(1*(1 - 2*N_R[i-1]))
}
plot(x = 1:steps, y = N_BH, las = 1, xlab = "Time steps", ylab = "Density", ylim = c(0, 0.5), pch = 16)
  lines(x = 1:steps, y = N_BH, col = "black", pch = 16)
points(x = 1:steps, y = N_H, col = "red", pch = 16)
  lines(x = 1:steps, y = N_H, col = "red")
points(x = 1:steps, y = N_R, col = "blue", pch = 16)
  lines(x = 1:steps, y = N_R, col = "blue")
